strictfp: A modifier introduced in JDK(1.2v). Applicable with methods & class.

public class A {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(10.0/3);// 3.333333333333, here we don't know how much 3 after decimal we get it depends upon OS architecture
    }
}

On different systems it give different output:
16 bit OS : 8-10 no. of 3 after decimal
31 bit OS : 12-14 no. of 3 after decimal
42 bit OS : 14-16 no. of 3 after decimal
Because we get different outputs, for uniformity we have to use strictfp modifier.
So, without strictfp we get platform dependent output, but after strictfp we get platform independent output.
Now it depends upon IEEE 754 standard (the universally adopted technical standard for representing and computing floating-point numbers in computer systems)
If we declare the whole class with strictfp that means every method present inside that class follw the IEE 754 standard.
As of release JDK 17, all floating point expressions are evaluated strictly and 'strictfp' is not required.

