volatile: A modifier, applicable only with variables.

Suppose we have int x = 5; and there are multiple threads that want to access the value of x which is 5,
t1 thread updated the value of x by 10
So t2 thread not getting tha actual value of x which is 5 t2 get the updated value of x by t1 which is 10
So, every new thread getting the value which is updated by the previous thread.

But if we use volatile with int x then local copy of x  will be provided to the threads.
volatile int x = 5;// master copy
now, if t1 thread try to access the value of x then the local copy of value of x which is 5 will be provided to the thread.
We can say that without volatile the problem of data inconsistency is occur.
Major disadvantage of volatile is if there are n no. of threads want to access the value of x then there are n no. of local copies have been made. Due to which we need high storage which leads to increase in space complexity.

transient: A modifier, applicable with variables. 

Serialization: Process of sending the object from one computer to another computer via the network.
Only instance variables, methods, block participates in serialization. static methods & variables does not participate in the serialization.
Inside object their are some information (username address), sensitive information as well (password) & we want to send this obj via network to the another machine and we want that our password does not go through the network due to the security purpose
for that we use 'transient' keyword with password, now JVM will provide a default value to the password that default value will pass through the network at the place of password.

